We have two Neo 550 on our elevator to control Coral. Our code allows us to control the speed of the Motors to either reverse or start to motors with a Xbox controller. However, whenever we startup up the robot it doesn’t work the first time we enable to robot. However, if we disable then re enable the robot the motor will work with the Xbox controller with no issues. Here is the code on GitHub: Robot-Source-Code-2025-Reefscape/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/GripperSubsystem.java at main · MCRobotics7045/Robot-Source-Code-2025-Reefscape The Command in Question is the RollerIn and RollerOut which are called in RobotContainer and they are defined in the Gripper Subsystem

The RollerIn and RollerOut commands have

@Override
public boolean isFinished() {
return false;
}
The motor is started in the
@Override
public void initialize() {
Gripper.RollerOut();
}
The execute() is blank.
Which means subsequent presses of the same button won’t do anything because the Command keeps running and initialize() won’t happen again. Since the commands require the subsystem, they will cancel the opposite command but won’t end on their own unless robot is disabled.
Make isFinished() return true;
The commands will run once and start the motor.
Suggestions for future:-
Use CommandXBoxController in RobotContainer. This eliminates the need for separately declaring JoystickButtons and allows
XBOX.b().onTrue(new RollerOut(GRIPPER));
Also take a look at inline commands which would eliminate the RollerOut command by writing
buttonX.onTrue(Commands.runOnce(()->GRIPPER.RollerOut()));

A better way to do it is to add commands like this in the GripperSubsystem

public Command rollerOutCommand() {
return Commands.runOnce(() → RollerOut(), this);
}

public Command rollerInCommand() {
return Commands.runOnce(() → RollerIn(), this);
}

public Command delayedRollerStartIn(double secs) {
return Commands.sequence(
Commands.waitSeconds(secs),
rollerInCommand());
}

Then RobotContainer becomes

buttonX.onTrue(GRIPPER.rollerOutCommand());

and
buttonB.onTrue( // Suck Coral Out
GRIPPER.delayedRollerStartIn(2));

and you can delete the RollerIn, RollerOut and DelayedRollerStart files. You’ll need to delete the imports for these also.
Be good to change to CommandXBoxController when you have only 3 buttons assigned and before a second controller is needed.
